<subSubSection id="C35A6576FFC31D17FF03F964FB18D767" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="597" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BFF36FDFFC31D16FF03F964FC45D09F" blockId="4.[151,1436,1596,1945]" box="[199,984,1740,1765]" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FF03F964FECCD09F" bold="true" box="[199,337,1740,1765]" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">Etymology:</emphasis>
Named after Pierre Sonnerat who discovered the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFF36FDFFC31D17FF03F958FB18D767" blockId="4.[151,1436,1596,1945]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="597" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">
The generic attribution is tentative, based on the pelage similarity between this animal and 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC31D16FB37F959FA09D173" baseAuthorityName="Lichtenstein" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[1267,1428,1776,1801]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Diplomesodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pulchellum">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FB37F959FA09D173" box="[1267,1428,1776,1801]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">D. pulchellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Sonnerat's shrew is however twice as long as the Central Asian species (head+body 
<quantity id="4CB89B18FFC31D16FB82F8BCFB5CD156" box="[1094,1217,1812,1837]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="7.6" metricValueMin="5.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="65.0" valueMax="76.0" valueMin="54.0">54–76 mm</quantity>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD14B0CFFC31D16FB08F8BCFAFDD157" box="[1228,1376,1812,1837]" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" refId="ref6419" refString="Nowak, R. M. (1999) Walker's mammals of the world. Vols. 1 &amp; 2. 6 th Edition. Johns Hopkins Press, Baltimore, lxx + 836 pp. &amp; x + 1100 pp. [pp. i - lxx + 1 - 836. &amp; pp. i - x + 837 - 1936]" type="book chapter">Nowak 1999</bibRefCitation>
), and if regularly larger than 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC31D16FE5AF891FDCCD12A" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1766" box="[414,593,1849,1872]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Suncus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="murinus">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FE5AF891FDCCD12A" box="[414,593,1849,1872]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">Suncus murinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as Sonnerat claimed, would make it the world's largest shrew. 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC31D16FAE7F891FA01D12A" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1766" box="[1315,1436,1849,1872]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Suncus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="murinus">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FAE7F891FA01D12A" box="[1315,1436,1849,1872]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">S. murinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ranges up to 
<quantity id="4CB89B18FFC31D16FEE2F8F4FE1FD10E" box="[294,386,1884,1909]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="150.0">150 mm</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFD14B0CFFC31D16FE54F8F4FDBFD10F" box="[400,546,1884,1909]" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" refId="ref6419" refString="Nowak, R. M. (1999) Walker's mammals of the world. Vols. 1 &amp; 2. 6 th Edition. Johns Hopkins Press, Baltimore, lxx + 836 pp. &amp; x + 1100 pp. [pp. i - lxx + 1 - 836. &amp; pp. i - x + 837 - 1936]" type="book chapter">Nowak 1999</bibRefCitation>
) or 
<quantity id="4CB89B18FFC31D16FD8BF8F4FD31D10E" box="[591,684,1884,1909]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" unit="mm" value="160.0">160 mm</quantity>
(Alfred 
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FCCFF8F6FCDED10F" box="[779,835,1884,1909]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">et al.</emphasis>
2006) in head and body length, making it roughly the same size as 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC31D16FEF7F829FE56D1E2" box="[307,459,1921,1944]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Diplomesodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sonneratii">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FEF7F829FE56D1E2" box="[307,459,1921,1944]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">D. sonneratii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as described by Sonnerat. 
<collectionCode id="ED51AE38FFC31D16FCCDF829FCDBD1E3" box="[777,838,1921,1945]" country="Australia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">DNA</collectionCode>
analysis (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD14B0CFFC31D16FC79F828FB09D1E3" box="[957,1172,1920,1945]" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" refId="ref5447" refString="Dubey, S., Salamin, N., Ruedi, M., Barriere, P., Colyn, M. &amp; Vogel, P. (2008) Biogeographic origin and radiation of the Old World crocidurine shrews (Mammalia: Soricidae) inferred from mitochondrial and nuclear genes. Molecular Phylogenetics &amp; Evolution, 48, 953 - 963. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2008.07.002" type="journal article">
Dubey 
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FBD0F829FBD2D1E3" box="[1044,1103,1920,1945]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
) nested 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC31D16FB3DF828FA01D1E3" authorityName="Brandt" authorityYear="1852" box="[1273,1436,1920,1945]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Diplomesodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="4" pageNumber="596" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC31D16FB3DF828FA01D1E3" box="[1273,1436,1920,1945]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="596">Diplomesodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within the speciose genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC21D17FE0AFF3FFDDFD6CA" box="[462,578,151,176]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Crocidura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="5" pageNumber="597" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC21D17FE0AFF3FFDDFD6CA" box="[462,578,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="597">Crocidura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, though the researchers decided, against the usual practice, to &quot;keep this morphologically highly distinctive taxon in its own genus, although this would render 
<taxonomicName id="4C404D7EFFC21D17FBBAFF14FB6FD6AF" box="[1150,1266,188,213]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Crocidura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="5" pageNumber="597" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B934EAEFFFC21D17FBBAFF14FB6FD6AF" box="[1150,1266,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="597">Crocidura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a paraphyletic taxon&quot;. Sonnerat’s shrew may not be extinct and should be searched for in southern 
<collectingCountry id="F357766DFFC21D17FBFEFF77FBEED682" box="[1082,1139,223,248]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="597">India</collectingCountry>
– if rediscovered, voucher specimens of each gender should be collected, and one specimen designated as a 
<typeStatus id="54FB885FFFC21D17FBE1FEADFB1CD767" box="[1061,1153,261,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="597">neotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
